The paper deals with the convex hull problem, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry, and analyzes the correctness of an algorithm for probabilistic points. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a new certificate error model for calculating geometric error, which falls under cs.PR (Probability), and analyzes the expected correctness of the algorithm, which involves statistical analysis and probability theory, making cs.ST (Statistics) a likely sub-category as well. The algorithm's time complexity is O(n log n), which suggests that it involves some form of sorting or searching, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of an algorithm's correctness, which involves numerical analysis and approximation, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category as well.
